This test is based on the Mockito Hello World Example:
https://examples.javacodegeeks.com/core-java/mockito/mockito-hello-world-example

Note: This code uses the old mockito 2.0.5-beta which is based on
cglib, while newer versions of mockito use byte-buddy. From
https://github.com/mockito/mockito-cglib:

"[mockito-cglib] Contains the integration with cglib which has been
discontinued in the core mockito in favor of ByteBuddy. The source
code kept here 'just in case' we need that in the future. We hope not
to ship Mockito with cglib any more."

Differences:

- Uses build.gradle instead of the original pom.xml.

- Test code is included in the sources (not in separate 'test'
  sub-directory), so that it can be fed into Doop.

- A driving main() has been added to MockitoHelloWorldExample, to make
  the test code reachable. Otherwise, in the absence of such a main()
  method, open-program analysis may happen, which is too generic for
  this test. (Alternatively, this can be automated if annotations such
  @Test or @BeforeMethod are seen by Doop.)

To analyze this project, 'gradle analyze' is not enough, as Soot may
miss some classes. You should use the "fat JAR" provided and post it
via gradle-plugin:

  (without HPROF information)
  build-tools% ./gradlew :gradle-plugin:replayPost -Pargs="full-path-to/fat-doop-project/"

  (with HPROF information)
  build-tools% ./gradlew :gradle-plugin:replayPost -Pargs="full-path-to/fat-doop-project-hprof/"
